stateDiagram-v2
    classDef okState fill:#dce7f2,stroke:#2e5f8a,stroke-width:1.5px,color:#1f2933
    classDef offState fill:#e8eaed,stroke:#6b7480,color:#1f2933
    classDef delState fill:#f2f4f7,stroke:#52606d,stroke-dasharray:4 3,color:#1f2933

    state "ACTIVE" as ACTIVE
    state "PENDING_ENROLLMENT" as PEND
    state "INACTIVE" as INACTIVE
    state "SUSPENDED" as SUSP
    state "Soft-deleted<br/><i>deleted_at set, status = INACTIVE</i>" as SOFTDEL

    [*] --> ACTIVE : self-registration or admin create
    [*] --> PEND : self-service tenant onboarding<br/>(first admin, e-mail unverified)

    PEND --> ACTIVE : e-mail ownership verified

    ACTIVE --> SUSP : admin suspends<br/>(policy / security)
    SUSP --> ACTIVE : admin reinstates

    ACTIVE --> INACTIVE : admin deactivates
    INACTIVE --> ACTIVE : admin reactivates

    ACTIVE --> SOFTDEL : DELETE user (GDPR/KVKK erasure)
    INACTIVE --> SOFTDEL : DELETE user
    SUSP --> SOFTDEL : DELETE user

    SOFTDEL --> [*] : purge job, daily 03:30<br/>after 30-day retention<br/>(ShedLock-guarded, flag-gated)

    note right of ACTIVE
        Temporary lockout is ORTHOGONAL to status:
        5 failed logins set is_locked + locked_until
        (+15 min) and logins answer HTTP 423;
        the lock auto-clears after the window.
    end note

    note left of SOFTDEL
        Soft delete = UPDATE, never DELETE FROM users
        (DB trigger forbids hard deletes).
        Reads exclude deleted rows via SQL restriction
        "deleted_at IS NULL".
    end note

    note right of INACTIVE
        Enum also declares LOCKED and DELETED;
        neither is ever assigned: lockout uses the
        flag pair, deletion uses deleted_at.
    end note

    class ACTIVE okState
    class INACTIVE offState
    class SUSP offState
    class SOFTDEL delState
